<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-09-14T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-09-14T12:00:00-05:00" n="484" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">123 Henderson, Loy W.: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in India</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                                    </gloss>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-09-14T13:00:00-04:00">September 14, 1951—1 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>607. For Henderson from McGhee. If you have not yet paid farewell
                                call on Nehru<note n="1" xml:id="d484fn1">Mr. Henderson was
                                    appointed Ambassador to Iran effective September 19; he departed
                                    from New Delhi on September 21.</note> you may wish consider
                                conveying to him as departing friend your forthright personal
                                observations on possible consequences to India if <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> fols present course in fon
                                relations. I leave to ur discretion the forcefulness with which you
                                may wish to present ur views. I am sure you will agree this occasion
                                may offer an opportunity to obtain from Nehru rather more realistic
                                and comprehensive views than he has heretofore expressed.
                                [McGhee.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>